															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/paladinfoster" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1439466); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1439466&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227296" alt="PaladinFoster" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1439466)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/paladinfoster" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1439466); return false;" >PaladinFoster</a></span> <span class="odate time_1517631013 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">03 Feb 2018 04:10</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3699193">
									

<p>Hmm, I’m not sure how I feel about that idea.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>So I had in the past gone with the idea that anartists largely make use of magic to produce their art(evidenced in my writing of SCP-1385, where the process of anart is hinted at). Ritualistic stuff that requires incantations, arcane gestures, and special materials like salts, blood, or crystals. You know, eye of newt and tongue of frog. This is generally how magic performed by wizards and warlocks is portrayed in D&amp;D, which I’m pretty a pretty avid player of.</p>
<p>However your idea here of Flow, that’s something wholly different. It’s instinctual, or perhaps a better word would be intuitional. It’s something done by feel and creative drive. That is not the magic of a wizard, that there is the magic of a bard. Actually the more I think about it the more I feel it fits. But it also makes me wonder why anart isn’t more common. Seems like any old artist with a lot of time and creativity would stumble into the Flow eventually. Was my #1 bro-chacho Vincent Van Gogh just not creative enough to touch the Flow? Or was he simply not born with the capacity to do so? Perhaps those questions are best left unanswered.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Anyway I like the idea of Flow more than I like the actual writing here. It’s not bad, it’s just not all that interesting compared to this thesis on the nature of anart.</p>

							</div>

								
					
