				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/sunnyclockwork" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1621343); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1621343&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227296" alt="SunnyClockwork" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1621343)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/sunnyclockwork" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1621343); return false;" >SunnyClockwork</a></span> <span class="odate time_1517644542 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">03 Feb 2018 07:55</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3699313">
									

<p>Yeah this was a pretty early execution of the concept, predates the other tales by 2 years or so. It's also one of my eariler tales and it has a lot of drawbacks. Those are no excuses for bad writing, of course; just saying that I'd like to keep it because it's an important part of the development of the concept, and personally I prefer writing new stuff than rewriting old stuff.</p>
<p>I'd say <a href="/torrent">Torrent</a> by Perelka_L is a much better potray of the concept, if you feel interested XD</p>
<p>As for why anart is not more common, I'd say that making something the world/the Flow &quot;feels right&quot; about is perhaps a little more tricky than making yourself feel right when creating things. Audience appeal and how &quot;good&quot; art is, or even how creative the artist is, are also a little different from how close the work is to the Flow. In short, the Flow thing doesn't necessarily relate to skills (for example, if situations are right, kids with no art training can do it), but is very hard to have access to; but it would be much eaiser if someone is to teach you or you happened upon it and try it a second time.</p>
<p>Past famous artists could have very well created anomalous work in this setting, but their anomalous properties may have been lost through the long time. The Foundation also may have expunged those that remained from public knowledge. But if you're unsatified with this answer, that's fair too.</p>
<p>Thank you for the feedback regardless.</p>

